I used the IRF460 because it didn’t require a heatsink and showed no signs of overheating in my setup. However, in general, the IRFP260N is a better choice for ZVS applications.
The main reason is that the IRF460 is designed for high-voltage operation (up to 500 V) but has relatively limited current capability (~20 A) and higher Rds(on), which leads to 
more heat at higher currents. ZVS drivers are typically low-voltage, high-current circuits, so current handling and low conduction losses are more important than high voltage rating.
The IRFP260N, although rated for a lower voltage (200 V), can handle much higher current (around 46–50 A) and has significantly lower Rds(on), making it more efficient and better suited for typical ZVS designs—provided a proper heatsink is used.
In my case, the circuit operates at around 12 V and ~10 A, so the IRF460 is not heavily stressed and performs adequately without additional cooling.
